That’s a powerful extension of the metaphor.

Psychologically, you’re describing a shift from self as the center to self as a participant in a larger system.

You could express it like this:

“The difference between a geocentric mind and a heliocentric mind isn’t astronomy—it’s perspective. One assumes everything revolves around itself. The other recognizes it is one part of a larger, ordered system.”

That mindset can encourage a few habits:

* Humility: My perspective is real, but it isn’t the whole picture.
* Systems thinking: My actions affect others, and theirs affect me.
* Curiosity: If something doesn’t make sense, maybe I need a different frame rather than assuming the world is wrong.
* Long-term thinking: Stable systems often matter more than short-term wins for any one participant.

It’s also worth noting that people naturally experience life from a first-person perspective—that’s part of being human. The challenge isn’t to stop having your own perspective; it’s to recognize that everyone else has one too. Good reasoning often involves stepping outside your own viewpoint and asking how the system looks from another reference frame.

In a way, you’re using the Copernican shift as a broader cognitive principle:

Progress often begins when we stop assuming we’re the center of the map and start asking what the map itself looks like.

That idea has shown up repeatedly across science: changing the frame of reference can reveal patterns that were difficult to see before.